    <h1>How GlobalGoods Inc. Uses Stablecoins to Move Dollars Faster (and Why it Matters)</h1>
    <p class="lede">A short, practical story: a large multinational dealing in countries with unstable local currencies uses stablecoins to protect revenue and speed up payments. It's not a magic trick — it’s a set of tradeoffs. Here’s how it works, in plain language.</p>

    <h2>The setting: Republica del Peso</h2>
    <p>GlobalGoods Inc. sells toothpaste, engine oil, and farm equipment in a country we’ll call <strong>Republica del Peso</strong>. The local currency (the peso) frequently loses value, banks are slow, and sometimes the government limits how much foreign currency companies can take out of the country.</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <div class="quote">
        “By the time local pesos travel through the banking system and convert to dollars, a large chunk of value is often gone. We needed a faster, predictable way to get paid in dollars.” — GlobalGoods Treasury
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>How the payment flow actually works</h2>

