    <h2>What GlobalGoods actually does with those stablecoins</h2>
    <div class="pros-cons">
      <div class="box">
        <strong>Short-term treasury of dollars</strong>
        <ul class="small">
          <li>Use to pay local suppliers or staff in other countries</li>
          <li>Convert a portion to bank dollars when convenient</li>
          <li>Lend small balances into low-risk institutional markets for yield</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="box">
        <strong>Operational benefits</strong>
        <ul class="small">
          <li>Payments arrive in <em>minutes</em>, not days</li>
          <li>Avoids capital controls and bank processing delays</li>
          <li>Keeps cash predictable and fungible across borders</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Quick numbers example</h2>
    <p class="small">If a distributor would otherwise wait 7 business days to transfer $2M (and the peso loses value each day), the speed and predictability of stablecoins can save the company the equivalent of thousands to millions in lost purchasing power depending on inflation and FX swings. For a multinational operating at scale, those savings add up fast.</p>

    <h2>Pros and Cons (summary)</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Pros</th><th>Cons</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Faster settlement (minutes)</td>
          <td>No built-in nominal interest — value erodes with inflation</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Reduces FX and banking friction</td>
          <td>Exposure to issuer risk (if the stablecoin issuer fails)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Programmable for automated treasury operations</td>
          <td>Regulatory or liquidity shocks can disrupt redemptions</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>The Risks Beneath the Calm Surface</h2>
    <p class="small">Yes — this setup is powerful, but not risk-free. Below are the main failure scenarios GlobalGoods’ treasury team watches closely.</p>

    <ul class="risk-list small">
      <li><strong>Run on the stablecoin issuer:</strong> If depositors rush to redeem stablecoins at once (because of a scandal, hack, or rumors), the issuer may not be able to convert reserves to cash quickly. That can break the $1 peg and temporarily shave value off each coin.</li>
      <li><strong>Liquidity mismatch:</strong> If the issuer holds assets that can’t be sold fast (illiquid securities, or reserves tied up in a failing bank), redemptions can be delayed or haircuts may be applied.</li>
      <li><strong>Regulatory shock:</strong> Sudden rules (freezes, bans, forced wind-downs) can prevent access to funds or make some markets unusable. This is why major corporates prefer fully audited, regulated stablecoins or institutional on-ramps.</li>
      <li><strong>Dollar depreciation / inflation:</strong> Stablecoins preserve nominal dollars, not purchasing power. If the U.S. dollar loses global value over years, the company’s dollar receipts still buy less.</li>
      <li><strong>Third-party platform risk:</strong> Using local crypto brokers or exchanges carries counterparty risk — KYC/AML issues, exchange hacks, or local restrictions can interrupt flows.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="panel">
      <strong>How GlobalGoods manages these risks</strong>
      <ul class="small">
        <li>Use multiple regulated stablecoin issuers (diversification).</li>
        <li>Limit the share of large balances held as stablecoins; convert to bank dollars on a schedule.</li>
        <li>Use custodial, institution-grade wallets and partners with insurance and audits.</li>
        <li>Have contingency plans: on-chain and off-chain exit routes, and FX hedges.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Final thought</h2>
    <p>For GlobalGoods, stablecoins are <em>not</em> an investment — they are a treasury tool. They trade off yield for speed, certainty, and fungibility. When used carefully and with strong controls, stablecoins can turn slow, risky cross-border receipts into reliable, moveable working capital — and for a large multinational operating in volatile markets, that’s often worth far more than the interest the company might have otherwise earned sitting in local banks.</p>

